== Leverage

#info[*Debt Ratio and Time Interest Earned*\

*$ "Debt Ratio" = "Total Liability"/"Total Asset" $*


The higher the ratio, the higher risk of investment is. That is, the asset of a company is mostly funded by debts.

*$ "Times-Interest Earned" = "Income from operations"/ "Interest Expense" $*

The higher the ratio the better the company is performing. It illustrates how number of times interest expense is earned

*$ "Leverage (Equity Multiplier) Ratio" = "Average Total Assets" / "Average Common Shareholders' Equity" $*

The higher the ratio, the higher risk of investment is. That is, the asset of a company is mostly funded by debts rather than equity.
]

== Profitability

#info[*Marigin/Percentage*\
\
$ "Revenue" - "Cost of Goods Sold" = "Gross Profit" $

$ "Gross Profit Marigin/Percentage (GPM)" = "Gross Profit" / "Net Sales" $

$ "Operating Profit Marigin/Percentage (OPM)" = "Operating Income" / "Net Sales" $

$ "Net Profit Marigin/Return on Sales (NPM)" = "Net Income" / "Net Sales" $

Revenue is also sales.

Net Sales $=$ Sales $-$ Allowances

The higher ratios are, the more profitable the company is.
]

